sols:
Our complex number is z=1+i. Therefore,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}|z|=\sqrt{1+1}=\sqrt{2}\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}\text{Arg}(z)=\arctan\left(\frac{1}{1}\right)=\arctan(1)=\frac{\pi}{4}\end{align*}

since the vector 1+i is in the first quadrant. Therefore,

\begin{align*}1+i=\sqrt{2}\exp\left(\frac{\pi}{4}i\right)\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}(1+i)^{10}=2^{10/2}\exp\left(\frac{10\pi}{4}i\right)=32\exp\left(\frac{5\pi}{2}i\right).\end{align*}

Now

\begin{align*}\exp\left(\frac{5\pi}{2}i\right)=\cos\left(\frac{5\pi}{2}\right)+i\sin\left(\frac{5\pi}{2}\right)=i\end{align*}

and therefore

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}(1+i)^{10}=32i.\end{align*}

hints:
Recall that polar form for a complex number \emph{z} is

\begin{align*}\displaystyle z=R\,\exp(i\theta)\end{align*}

where \emph{R} is the modulus of \emph{z} and $\theta$ is the argument.
